/**
 * LanguageModelV3 adapter for GitLab Duo Agent Platform (DWS).
 *
 * Maps DWS WebSocket events to the Vercel AI SDK streaming protocol:
 *   newCheckpoint (text)  → text-delta
 *   runMcpTool             → tool-call (emitted for UI visibility)
 *   workflow COMPLETED     → finish(stop)
 *   workflow FAILED        → error
 *
 * IMPORTANT: Tool execution architecture
 * =======================================
 * DWS drives the agentic loop server-side. When DWS requests a tool via
 * `runMcpTool`, we execute it ourselves using the AI SDK tools passed in
 * `options.tools`, send the result back to DWS via WebSocket `actionResponse`,
 * and keep streaming. The stream stays open until DWS sends COMPLETED/FAILED.
 *
 * This means the AI SDK's outer tool loop (which would call doStream() again
 * with tool results in messages) is NOT used for workflow models. The entire
 * agentic conversation happens within a single doStream() call.
 *
 * We still emit `tool-call` stream parts so the UI can show tool usage,
 * but finishReason is always 'stop' (never 'tool-calls').
 *
 * Lifecycle per doStream() call:
 *   1. Get workflow token  (POST /duo_workflows/direct_access)
 *   2. Create workflow     (POST /duo_workflows/workflows)
 *   3. Connect WebSocket   (wss://.../duo_workflows/ws)
 *   4. Send startRequest   (with goal, tools, context)
 *   5. Stream events       (checkpoint → text, tool request → execute → respond)
 *   6. Close on finish     (COMPLETED/FAILED/CANCELLED)
 *
 * SECURITY MODEL — Tool Execution
 * =================================
 * This library acts as a **bridge** between DWS (server) and the host's tool
 * system (e.g., Exos Agent).  It does NOT execute host-OS commands itself except
 * for the read-only `git` calls inside `getGitInfo()` (fixed argument lists,
 * no user-controlled data, via `execFile`).
 *
 * Built-in tool mapping (`mapBuiltinTool`)
 * -----------------------------------------
 * DWS built-in tools are mapped to structured host-tool invocations that the
 * host's `toolExecutor` callback then executes through its own permission
 * system.  For tools that ultimately produce shell commands the following
 * defences are applied:
 *
 *   • `shellEscape()` — wraps every argument in single quotes and escapes
 *     embedded single quotes, preventing metacharacter injection for all
 *     argument-based tools (runCommand, runGitCommand, mkdir, runHTTPRequest).
 *
 *   • `validateNoShellMetachars()` — rejects program names and git sub-commands
 *     containing `;`, `&`, `|`, `` ` ``, `$`, `(`, `)`, `<`, `>` before they
 *     reach shellEscape, providing a defence-in-depth check.
 *
 *   • `runShellCommand` — intentionally passes the command string through
 *     **without sanitization** because it is a deliberately raw shell tool.
 *     The host's `toolExecutor` / permission system is the final gate and must
 *     decide whether to allow it.  A length cap (10 000 chars) limits DoS via
 *     oversized payloads.
 *
 *   • `runHTTPRequest` — only `http://` and `https://` URL schemes are allowed
 *     (allowlist); all others (file://, gopher://, ftp://, etc.) are rejected.
 *     A `--` separator before the URL prevents flag injection via paths like
 *     `--output /tmp/evil`.
 *
 *   • `mkdir` — rejects null bytes in the directory path.
 *
 * Error sanitization
 * -------------------
 * All error messages forwarded into the stream (tool catch blocks, failed
 * events, WebSocket close reasons) are passed through `sanitizeErrorMessage()`
 * which redacts Bearer tokens, GitLab PAT/CI tokens, and URL credential query
 * parameters before they are surfaced to callers or logged.
 *
 * Trust boundary
 * ---------------
 * DWS is treated as a **trusted server** for the purpose of tool invocation —
 * it controls which tools are called and with what arguments.  Consumers MUST
 * implement their own authorization layer in the `toolExecutor` callback
 * (e.g., user confirmation prompts, allow-lists) for any tool that can cause
 * side effects on the user's machine.
 */

